Source Plan Reference
Use this reference when creating citation plans, evaluating evidence strength, or preparing a fact-check list for health and wellness articles.
Source Hierarchy
Prefer sources in this order:
Current clinical guidelines, public health agencies, and professional associations.
Systematic reviews and meta-analyses.
Large randomized controlled trials.
Observational studies with clear limitations.
Academic medical centers and medically reviewed patient education.
Official product labels, regulatory pages, and safety notices.
Expert interviews, clearly attributed and credentialed.
Avoid using forums, anecdotal testimonials, brand sales pages, influencer posts, or non-reviewed summaries as evidence for health claims.
Evidence Labels
Use these labels in briefs and claim audits:
Strong: supported by guidelines, systematic reviews, or consistent high-quality evidence.
Moderate: supported by credible studies but with limitations, mixed results, or population constraints.
Emerging: early evidence, small studies, plausible mechanism, or limited replication.
Traditional or anecdotal: common use but limited clinical evidence.
Unsupported: no reliable source found or claim exceeds evidence.
Unsafe: claim could cause harm, delay care, or mislead readers.
Citation Plan Format
For each section, list:
Claim to verify
Ideal source type
Example source target
Evidence strength
Required caveat
Expert review needed: yes/no
Currentness
Treat these as time-sensitive and verify before publication:
Supplement safety and interactions
Medication, pregnancy, pediatric, or chronic-condition guidance
Public health recommendations
Disease screening or prevention guidance
Legal, regulatory, advertising, or labeling claims
Product comparisons or ingredient claims
Source Use Rules
Do not cite a source the agent has not actually checked.
Do not cite a study for a broader population, condition, or outcome than it studied.
Do not turn correlation into causation.
Do not bury important limitations.
Use dates when guidelines or recommendations may change.
